				<p><p>I can say:"Yes it works"</p>

<p>Are there any recommendation not doing this? I cannot say, but it works. </p>

<p>The problem you may get is with a weak design. You have to be sure, that there is not any switch/sensor/relay/wire which is able to bypass the main switch.</p>

<p>I'm not sure whether the PC-switch will work, because a computer usually has a power consumption of less then 1000W. This means a current of around 5Amps (10Amps for the US).</p>

<p>If you draw around 20Amps, this may exceed the capability of the switch.</p>

<p>I suggest using an EMO switch.They usually can handle currents of 50Amps+ and it you know what to do with something went wrong. Just Smash it.</p>
